SIMPLE: witch
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Witch
<hw>Witch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Wick</er> of a
lamp.]</ety> <def>A cone of paper which is placed in a vessel of lard or
other fat, and used as a taper.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Witch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Witch
<hw>Witch</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>wicche</ets>, AS.
<ets>wicce</ets>, fem., <ets>wicca</ets>, masc.; perhaps the same word
as AS. <ets>w⟦imac⟧tiga</ets>, <ets>w⟦imac⟧tga</ets>, a soothsayer (cf.
<er>Wiseacre</er>); cf. Fries. <ets>wikke</ets>, a witch, LG.
<ets>wikken</ets> to predict, Icel. <ets>vitki</ets> a wizard,
<ets>vitka</ets> to bewitch.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>One who practices the black art, or magic; one
regarded as possessing supernatural or magical power by compact with an
evil spirit, esp. with the Devil; a sorcerer or sorceress; -- now
applied chiefly or only to women, but formerly used of men as
well.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There was a man in that city whose name was Simon, a
<qex>witch</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Wyclif (Acts viii. 9).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He can not abide the old woman of Brentford; he swears she's a
<qex>witch</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An ugly old woman; a hag.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who exercises more than common power of
attraction; a charming or bewitching person; also, one given to
mischief; -- said especially of a woman or child.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>A certain curve of the third
order, described by <person>Maria Agnesi</person> under the name
<altname>versiera</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The stormy petrel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A Wiccan; an adherent or practitioner of
<er>Wicca</er>, a religion which in different forms may be paganistic
and nature-oriented, or ditheistic. The term <ex>witch</ex> applies to
both male and female adherents in this sense.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Witch balls</b></col>, <cd>a name applied to the
interwoven rolling masses of the stems of herbs, which are driven by the
winds over the steppes of Tartary. Cf. <er>Tumbleweed</er>.</cd>
<au>Maunder (Treas. of Bot.)</au> -- <col><b>Witches' besoms</b></col>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>tufted and distorted branches of the silver fir,
caused by the attack of some fungus.</cd> <au>Maunder (Treas. of
Bot.)</au> -- <col><b>Witches' butter</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a
name of several gelatinous cryptogamous plants, as <spn>Nostoc
commune</spn>, and <spn>Exidia glandulosa</spn>. See
<er>Nostoc</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Witch grass</b></col>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a kind of grass (<spn>Panicum capillare</spn>)
with minute spikelets on long, slender pedicels forming a light, open
panicle.</cd> -- <col><b>Witch meal</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>,
<cd>vegetable sulphur. See under <er>Vegetable</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>witch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: witch
<hw>witch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>witched</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>witching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>wiccian</ets>.]</ety>
<def>To bewitch; to fascinate; to enchant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[I 'll] <qex>witch</qex> sweet ladies with my words and looks.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whether within us or without⟦br⟧
The spell of this illusion be⟦br⟧
That <qex>witches</qex> us to hear and see.</q>
<rj><qau>Lowell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>witchcraft</ent>⟦br⟧
